body:
**Do you want to request a *feature* or report a *bug*?**
*feature*


**What is the current behavior?**
In every react project I've worked there is always some sort of code that looks like this:

```javascript
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
    render() {
        if (!this.props.foo && !this.props.bar && !this.props.foobar) return null;
        return (
            <div>
                {this.props.foo && <h2>{this.props.foo}</h2>}
                {this.props.bar && <h3>{this.props.bar}</h3>}
                {this.props.foobar && <h4>{this.props.foobar}</h4>}
            </div>
        );
    }
}
```

This looks ugly and not very scalable(imagine MyComponent has 15 children instead of just 3) but is (to my knowledge) the only way to achieve the intended behavior

**What is the expected behavior?**
A prop such as "nullIfEmpty"(naming sugestions are welcome) that defaults to false and if specified to true will not render an element with no children.

```javascript
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
    render() {
        return (
            <div nullIfEmpty={true}>
                <h2 nullIfEmpty={true}>{this.props.foo}</h2>
                <h3 nullIfEmpty={true}>{this.props.bar}</h3>
                <h4 nullIfEmpty={true}>{this.props.foobar}</h4>
            </div>
        );
    }
}
```

Looks better, scales better, and keeps my (*and probably not only my own*) OCD at ease.
